		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						The proofe will shewe itself: owr old saying.
						The issu will prooue itself.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="proofe will shewe itself" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Acta loquantur: aut
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="ES">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Todos es nada.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Actions speak, else everything is for naught.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Non Sufficit
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						desiderium eminùs: sine instanti inuentione,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						et dispositione cominùs.
						Nondum
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						verus est,
						solidusq[ue] Logicus, qui nescit Inuenire, quicquid qua[e]rit:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut iudicare,
						quicq[ui]d inuenit. 
						Tanta est Logica[e] facultas,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						id est, artificiosa[e] rationis: siquis cognouerit
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						vti.
						In primisq[ue], Foelix
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						qui potuit rerum cognoscere causas: sed subtiliter,						
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						id est,
						tam
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						in specie,
						et indiuiduo, quàm in genere. Et,
						si quod est Singulare arcanum, etiam profundè.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				An aloof desire is not enough without some present discovery and immediate arrangement.
				A logician is not yet true or solid if he does not know how to discover whatever it is that he seeks,
				or how to judge whatever it is that he finds. So great is the faculty of logic (that is, of artificial reason);
				if any one knew how to use it.
				
				And especially happy is he who is capable of recognizing causes, though with subtlety;
				that is, both in the species and individual case, as well as in the genus.
				And if whatever is singular is mysterious, it must even be done profoundly.	
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
